data.title: Oil on Track for Monthly Loss Ahead of OPEC+ Meeting — Market Talk
data.description: Oil prices are headed for a monthly loss of nearly 3% ahead of Sunday's OPEC+ meeting. In early trade, Brent crude and WTI both slip 0.6% to $63.98 and $60.20 a barrel, respectively. The market has largely priced in a modest output increase of 137,000 barrels a day for December, but concerns over a growing supply glut continue to weigh on sentiment. Meanwhile, the trade agreement between the U.S. and China did little to resolve questions over Chinese purchases of Russian oil, analysts say. "There has been no indication on the Chinese side as to whether they will stop buying," according to ANZ. "There was also hope that China would agree to purchases of U.S. oil and gas as part of a broader U.S.-China deal." (giulia.petroni@wsj.com)

AJ Bell plc ("AJ Bell" or the "Company")

Total Voting Rights

In accordance with rule 5.6.1 of the FCA's Disclosure Guidance and Transparency Rules, the Company announces that, as at 31 October 2025, its issued share capital consisted of 402,862,080 ordinary shares of £0.000125 pence each, with each share carrying the right to one vote.

There are no shares held in Treasury. Therefore, the total number of voting rights in the Company is 402,567,881.

The above figure may be used by shareholders as the denominator for the calculation by which they may determine if they are required to notify their interest in, or change to their interest in, the Company under the FCA's Disclosure Guidance and Transparency Rules.

data.title: Hong Kong's Economy in Better Shape Than Expected, Growth Estimates Show
data.description:
(08:30 GMT) *HK 3Q Advance GDP +3.8% on Year; Market Expected +3.0%
(08:31 GMT) *HK 3Q Advance GDP +0.7% on Quarter Seasonally Adjusted
(09:10 GMT) Hong Kong's Economy in Better Shape Than Expected, Growth Estimates Show

By Fabiana Negrin Ochoa

Hong Kong's economy appears to be performing better than expected, with growth estimates on Friday reinforcing signs of recovery.

Gross domestic product grew 3.8% in real terms from a year earlier in the third quarter, advance data showed, picking up from the 3.1% pace set in the prior two quarters.

The robust third-quarter performance was driven by a continued surge in exports and sustained expansion in domestic demand, the statistics department said. The figure beat expectations for 3.0% growth in a Wall Street Journal poll.

Strong demand for electronic products and resilient regional trade flows buoyed exports, which rose 12.2% in real terms in the July-September period, meeting economists' expectations for despite global trade uncertainty.

Growth improved on a seasonally adjusted quarter-over-quarter basis, with GDP expanding 0.7% in the third quarter compared with 0.4% in the second quarter.

Looking ahead, officials in the Asian financial hub said they expect solid growth for the rest of 2025. Supporting that outlook are expectations for continued, though moderate, global economic growth, and U.S. interest rate cuts, which should boost asset-market sentiment, the statistics department said.

"Coupled with a gradual recovery in consumption confidence and also a visible improvement in business sentiment from earlier this year, these developments should lend support to local consumption and investment activity," it added.

Government measures to stimulate the economy and markets will also provide support, though external uncertainties, especially around trade barriers, still warrant close monitoring, it said.

Separate data on retail sales for September added to signs of life emerging in Hong Kong's economy after years of lackluster growth. The retail sector's recovery continued last month, with sales rising in both values and volume--an indication that consumer demand is holding up.

Write to Fabiana Negrin Ochoa at fabiana.negrinochoa@wsj.com

data.title: Hong Kong September retail sales rise 5.9% from a year earlier
data.description:
Hong Kong's retail sales by value in September rose 5.9% from a year earlier, the fifth straight month of gains, government data showed on Friday.

Sales increased to HK$31.3 billion ($4.03 billion). In August, retail sales rose 3.9% from the same month the year before.

In volume terms, September retail sales increased by 4.8% from a year earlier, compared with a revised 3.4% rise in August.

For the first nine months of 2025, the value of total retail sales declined by 1% from the same period in 2024, and volume fell 2.3%.

"Looking ahead, improving local consumer sentiment and sustained growth in inbound tourism should continue to render support to retail businesses," a government spokesperson said.

Visitor arrivals in September surged to 3.29 million, up 8% from the same month a year earlier, according to Hong Kong Tourism Board data.

Mainland Chinese visitors accounted for 2.46 million of these arrivals, a 7% increase year-on-year.

Sales of jewellery, watches, clocks and valuable gifts rose 9.1% year-on-year in September after a revised 16.4% increase in August.

Sales of clothing, footwear and allied products fell 10.2% year-on-year in September following a revised 2.8% rise in August.

($1 = 7.7675 Hong Kong dollars)

data.title: Saint-Gobain shares slide as Americas performance disappoints
data.description:
** Shares of French building materials producer Saint-Gobain fall nearly 3% following broadly in line quarterly update but weaker-than-expected sales in the Americas

** RBC Europe analysts attribute the US volume decline to muted construction activity and flat Americas margins

** "Typically, 10% of roofing demand is derived from extreme weather events - a lack of hurricanes this year has therefore weighed on volumes, particularly against a tough comparison base of 2024," RBC adds in a note

** Jefferies analysts say that Americas reported weaker-than-expected like-for-like (lfl) sales (-2.9%) with North America's 6.9% drop due to residential new build weakness and subdued storm season volumes, while Latin America partially offset this with a growth of 6.4%

** Glynis Johnson of Jefferies sees downward pressure on Saint-Gobain's FY25 margins from the regional sales mix but notes potential operating leverage improvement in Europe and storm season recovery in 2026

** The stock is at the bottom of France CAC40 index

data.title: FTSE MIB Hits Three-Week High
data.description:
The FTSE MIB rose 0.4% to around 43,350 in early trading on Friday, hitting its highest level in three weeks and outperforming most of its European peers.

The index is also heading for a second consecutive weekly gain, finishing a busy week of central bank announcements, US-China trade updates, and a wave of corporate and economic reports.

It is also on track for its fourth monthly advance.

Heavyweight financial stocks propelled the FTSE MIB higher, led by Intesa Sanpaolo (+1.1%), which climbed to its highest level in nearly two decades.

Its peers Bper Banca and Azimut Holding also grew 1.3% and 1.8%, respectively.

Other notable gainers included Interpump Group (+5.2%), Prysmian (+2.8%), Stellantis (+1.4%), and Amplifon (+1.5%).

Market attention is now turning to today’s Eurozone inflation data, which could provide key guidance for the ECB’s upcoming policy decisions.

data.title: Key facts: Toyota invests $3B in India; plans reverse imports to Japan
data.description:
• Toyota Motor is investing $3 billion to boost production in India, building a new plant in Maharashtra to produce over 1 million cars yearly across two sites.1
  • Toyota Motor plans to reverse import U.S.-made cars to Japan, including the Camry sedan. Specific models and costs are not confirmed, pending favorable conditions.2
  • Toyota is exploring reverse imports, a strategy it is considering alongside Nissan, with both companies estimating potential volumes of around 20,000 cars per year.3

data.title: Key facts: Samsung, Nvidia Discuss Partnership; HBM3E Sales Boost Shares
data.description:
• Samsung's Jay Y. Lee met Nvidia's Jensen Huang to discuss their partnership. Analysts suggest that supplying HBM4 chips could boost Samsung's market share in advanced memory.1
  • Samsung Electronics is selling its HBM3E chips, including 12-layer versions to Nvidia, as it aims to recover from past weak earnings linked to the AI memory chip market.2
  • Samsung Electronics closed at 107,500 won on the latest trading day, marking an increase of 3,400 won or 3.27% from the previous closing price.3

data.title: Key facts: Hyundai invests $5B in India; partners with Nvidia for AI
data.description:
• Hyundai Motor announced a $5 billion investment to expand its manufacturing and research operations in India, aiming to enhance its presence in the growing Indian automotive market.1
  • Analysts from UBS and Nomura expect that Hyundai's upcoming product launches and strong SUV pipeline will improve its product mix and market share in the latter half of the year, supporting growth.2
  • Hyundai Motor (005380) is partnering with Nvidia to invest $3 billion in a venture focused on developing AI, including a supercomputer for in-vehicle systems, autonomous driving, and robotics.3
